There are two things in our render() method to take note of. First, note how the moduleâ€™s content setting is handled. Module settings defined with field type tiny_mce (like the content setting in our module) require the use of a special React Component. The builder sets up the required component and then passes it down to the module as the setting value. Since the value is not a string or number and is actually a React Component, we need to use it as such in our JSX markup.

Also note how we wrapped our moduleâ€™s output in a Fragment component. Fragments allow you to return multiple top-level elements from your render() method without actually adding an extra element to the page itself.

CSS Styles

Styles for our module can be defined using the style.css file in its directory. Our custom header module is pretty basic so it doesnâ€™t require much styling. Though we should add some bottom margin for the heading so that there is some space between it and the content below it. Later, in our Divi Builder Module In-Depth tutorial series youâ€™ll learn how to make margin and padding for the heading (or any element inside your moduleâ€™s output) configurable from within the moduleâ€™s settings.

For now, letâ€™s go ahead and update our moduleâ€™s style.css:

	.simp-simple-header-heading {
		margin-bottom: 20px;
	}
